POINTS:
- [lib/trino-parquet/src/main/java/io/trino/parquet/reader/ParquetReader.java:516] `initializePageReader` reads from the `ChunkedInputStream`, which materializes the first `ChunkReader` — up to 8MB (`maxBufferSize`). The old code performed a targeted small I/O to read just the dictionary page (~KB) for each candidate column. For row groups that are ultimately pruned by dictionary filtering, this turns a few-KB read into an up-to-8MB read per candidate column.

This compounds with multiple candidate columns. Given `WHERE col_a = 'x' AND col_b = 'y' AND col_c = 'z'`, this method calls `initializePageReader` for each candidate sequentially. If `col_c` finally prunes the row group, we've already materialized up to 8MB per preceding candidate column that gets discarded.

**Suggested fix:** Split the column chunk `DiskRange` at the dictionary/data page boundary for candidate columns in the `ParquetReader` constructor. `FilteredOffsetIndex.calculateOffsetRanges` already does this when column index filtering is active. Extend this to the no-column-index case:

```java
// In the ParquetReader constructor, when filteredOffsetIndex == null
if (isCandidateForDictionaryMatch && firstDataPageOffset > startingPosition) {
    ranges.put(key, new DiskRange(startingPosition, firstDataPageOffset - startingPosition));
    ranges.put(key, new DiskRange(firstDataPageOffset, totalLength - (firstDataPageOffset - startingPosition)));
} else {
    ranges.put(key, new DiskRange(startingPosition, totalLength));
}
```

For large columns (where over-reading matters), `mergeAdjacentDiskRanges` won't re-merge these because their combined length exceeds `maxBufferSize`. The dictionary stays as its own small `ChunkReader`, so `initializePageReader` only reads the dictionary chunk. If the row group is pruned, the data `ChunkReader`s are freed unread via `ChunkedInputStream.close()`. For small columns, the ranges merge back — but total size is small, so there's no meaningful regression.
